A quick start To Pytank¶

¡Welcome to Pytank!¶

Pytank is a Python tool designed to estimate hydrocarbon reserves, with a focus on under-saturated reservoirs. Its main feature is the creation of objects such as “well”, “tank” and “aquifer” to facilitate the analysis.

In this tutorial, you will learn how to develop the different objects that Pytank uses for its operation. Mastering these concepts will be indispensable for you to be able to perform customized analysis according to your needs. In addition, you can refer to the Pytank API, which explains Pytank functions in more detail.

Once you have completed this introductory tutorial, you are ready to explore the various options and advanced features Pytank offers. From here, you will be able to access specific guides and practical examples to get the most out of this tool.

A note on data formats¶

In Pytank, a variety of data types are handled, including text strings (str), integers (int), floating point numbers (float), and boolean values (bool). These data types comprise both the parameters of Pytank objects and the input data used in analyses.

Pytank allows the generation of a variety of plots that facilitate the understanding of reservoir behavior using historical production and pressure data as well as geological information.

It is essential to consider the structure of the data when using Pytank. The library was initially designed with specific column names which are as follows:

User Constants Pytank Constants
DATE_COL "START_DATETIME"
PRESSURE_COL "PRESSURE_DATUM"
PRESSURE_PVT_COL "Pressure"
TANK_COL "Tank"
WELL_COL "WELL_BORE"
OIL_CUM_COL "OIL_CUM"
OIL_VOL_COL "OIL_VOL"
WATER_CUM_COL "WATER_CUM"
GAS_CUM_COL "GAS_CUM"
LIQUID_CUM "LIQ_CUM"
OIL_FVF_COL "Bo"
GAS_FVF_COL "Bg"
GAS/OIL_RATIO_COL "GOR"
INJECTION_WATER "WATER_VOL" 
Therefore, if you want to start working with **Pytank**, it is recommended to pay attention to the column names in the different datasets you own, as this may impact the sequence of operation of the different **Pytank** modules. Once this is clear, you can start using **Pytank**.

1. Importing Libraries and Data¶

The first step is to import the necessary libraries and load the data from CSV files. This includes fluid properties, production and pressure data, which are transformed into Pandas DataFrames for further manipulation.

In [2]:
Copied! 
# Libraries
import pandas as pd

# Modules
from pytank.fluid_model import OilModel, WaterModel
from pytank.tank import Tank
from pytank.analysis import Analysis
from pytank.aquifer_model import Fetkovich, CarterTracy
from pytank.functions.helpers import create_wells, search_wells

# Data
df_pvt = pd.read_csv("example_data/pvt.csv"
                     )
df_production = pd.read_csv("example_data/production.csv"
                            )
df_pressures = pd.read_csv("example_data/pressures.csv"
                           )
# Libraries import pandas as pd # Modules from pytank.fluid_model import OilModel, WaterModel from pytank.tank import Tank from pytank.analysis import Analysis from pytank.aquifer_model import Fetkovich, CarterTracy from pytank.functions.helpers import create_wells, search_wells # Data df_pvt = pd.read_csv("example_data/pvt.csv" ) df_production = pd.read_csv("example_data/production.csv" ) df_pressures = pd.read_csv("example_data/pressures.csv" )

2. Creating Well(s)¶

Using the production and pressure data, well objects are created using the create_wells() function. This allows users to select and work with a specific set of wells.

In [57]:
Copied! 
wells = create_wells(df_prod=df_production,
                     df_press=df_pressures,
                     freq_prod="MS",
                     freq_press=None)

# List of wells for user selection
my_wells = [
    "A-1-P", "A-10-P", "A-11-P", "A-12-P", "A-13-P", "A-14-P", "A-16-P",
    "A-17-P"
]

# lis of wells with the pressure and production info for user selection
wells_info = search_wells(wells, my_wells)
wells = create_wells(df_prod=df_production, df_press=df_pressures, freq_prod="MS", freq_press=None) # List of wells for user selection my_wells = [ "A-1-P", "A-10-P", "A-11-P", "A-12-P", "A-13-P", "A-14-P", "A-16-P", "A-17-P" ] # lis of wells with the pressure and production info for user selection wells_info = search_wells(wells, my_wells)

3. Fluid modeling¶

Fluid models are defined for oil and water. These models are essential for accurate calculations in the subsequent analysis.

In [58]:
Copied! 
oil_model = OilModel(data_pvt=df_pvt,
                     temperature=25)

water_model = WaterModel(salinity=3000,
                         temperature=200,
                         unit=1)
oil_model = OilModel(data_pvt=df_pvt, temperature=25) water_model = WaterModel(salinity=3000, temperature=200, unit=1)

4. Tank Configuration¶

A Tank object representing the reservoir is created. This object includes information about the wells, fluid models and other relevant parameters, such as the productivity index (PI) and aquifer properties.

In [59]:
Copied! 
tank = Tank(name="Zone_B",
            wells=wells_info,
            oil_model=oil_model,
            water_model=water_model,
            pi=3700,
            swo=0.25,
            cw=3.5e-6,
            cf=4.6e-6,
            aquifer=None)

5. Data Analysis¶

An analysis is carried out using the Analysis object, which allows various evaluations of the tank behavior. This includes the generation of graphs and the application of analytical methods.

In [61]:
Copied! 
analysis = Analysis(tank_class=tank,
                    freq="12M",
                    position="end")

plt = analysis.plot_press_avg_time()
analysis = Analysis(tank_class=tank, freq="12M", position="end") plt = analysis.plot_press_avg_time()

6. Graphical Methods¶

The results of the analysis are visualized through graphs generated by methods of the Analysis class, such as Campbell's graph and Havlena's method. This provides a visual representation of reservoir behavior and production.

Campbell Plot¶

With campbell's graph you will be able to determine if there is an aquifer that has some contribution to your reservoir, and if so, identify the magnitude of the energy contribution.

In [54]:
Copied! 
camp = analysis.campbell_plot()
camp = analysis.campbell_plot()

Havlena Odeh Plot¶

The Havlena Odeh chart will help you obtain the OOIP value based on the information used in your initial analysis.

In [55]:
Copied! 
ho = analysis.havlena_odeh_plot()
ho = analysis.havlena_odeh_plot()

7. Aquifer Models¶

If necessary, aquifer models, such as Fetkovich or Carter-Tracy, can be included for a more detailed analysis, assuming that in our Campbell graph we have managed to note that there is an influence of an aquifer on the reservoir. Therefore it will be necessary to define the properties of the aquifer and create a new Tank object that includes it.

Aquifer Model with Fetkovich¶

In [67]:
Copied! 
aq_radius = 14000
res_radius = 2000
aq_thickness = 20
phi = 0.25
ct = 0.000007
theta = 290
k = 25
water_visc = 0.6

fet = Fetkovich(
    aq_radius=aq_radius,
    res_radius=res_radius,
    aq_thickness=aq_thickness,
    aq_por=phi,
    ct=ct,
    theta=theta,
    k=k,
    water_visc=water_visc,
)
aq_radius = 14000 res_radius = 2000 aq_thickness = 20 phi = 0.25 ct = 0.000007 theta = 290 k = 25 water_visc = 0.6 fet = Fetkovich( aq_radius=aq_radius, res_radius=res_radius, aq_thickness=aq_thickness, aq_por=phi, ct=ct, theta=theta, k=k, water_visc=water_visc, )

Create your tank using your Aquifer for your analysis based on the behavior of your data¶

In [68]:
Copied! 
tank_fet = Tank(name="Zone_B",
                wells=wells_info,
                oil_model=oil_model,
                water_model=water_model,
                pi=3700,
                swo=0.25,
                cw=3.5e-6,
                cf=4.6e-6,
                aquifer=fet)

analysis_fet = Analysis(tank_class=tank_fet,
                        freq="MS",
                        position="end",
                        smooth=True)

8. Analytical Method¶

The Pytank analysis module includes an additional function to the graphical method to evaluate the accuracy of the results obtained by the Havlena and Odeh approach: the analytical method.

This method is based on an “inferred OOIP”, which allows to recalculate a synthetic pressure. The inferred OOIP becomes relevant when the observed reservoir pressure behaves similarly to the calculated synthetic pressure. If both pressures match, it can be confirmed that the inferred well is suitable for the material balance equation.

In [73]:
Copied! 
analytic_meth_fet = analysis_fet.analytic_method(poes=67e+6, option="plot")
analytic_meth_fet = analysis_fet.analytic_method(poes=67e+6, option="plot")
